.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S_F6iXdleeI/AAAAAAAAADg/Dtl0EEPTsJk/s1600/spock_tpau.jpg"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 360px; height: 240px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S_F6iXdleeI/AAAAAAAAADg/Dtl0EEPTsJk/s400/spock_tpau.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5472289753064110562" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="mso-bidi-mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;font-family:Calibri;color:#333333;"><br /></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Last night we were watching the PBS special </span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FF6666;">“</span><a href="http://www.pbs.org/thisemotionallife/"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FF6666;">This Emotional Life</span></a><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FF6666;">,” </span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">a fascinating look at the biological and social aspects of human relationships.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The first episode looks at parent/child bonding, friendship, bullying, and marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Romance and marriage:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">I try to pretend that cultural differences don’t matter within OUR marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">I want to believe that what matters is that we fell in love with each other, but I sometimes feel like I’ve landed on the planet Vulcan.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">No, seriously, sometimes I can’t help but visualize my mother-in-law as the Vulcan lady with the Yiddish accent asking Spock if Vulcan ceremonies are for “out-verlders.”</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">After watching the program, which featured several American families and their emotional interactions, I asked my husband if his mother, or another Indian of his mother’s generation, watched the episode, would she find it totally alien?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The answer:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">an immediate, emphatic, unequivocal “yes.”</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The families and couples profiled in the documentary were trying to resolve interpersonal conflicts, trying to restore the romance in their relationships, and working to improve their own sense of fulfillment as well as working towards making their partners fulfilled and happy.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">The couples wanted to improve their communication skills as well as their sex lives.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">But for my mother-in-law, as well as for my husband’s aunts, and even some of his cousins, that view would be completely alien, even contradictory to what they have been taught.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">And as we talked more, I started to wonder if we have a cavernous divide between our ideas of marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"> </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Obviously, not everyone’s family is the same, and if you or your partner come from a particularly wealthy or highly educated family, this might not be true for your situation.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">My husband’s family, however, is extremely middle class—the group that adheres most closely to the social mores or any culture.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Maybe your partner grew up in a household in which the husband and wife were equal and spoke to each other affectionately at home.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">When asked if his parents had an affectionate relationship or treated each other as equals, my husband says that his parents simply put up with one another and got used to one another.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">For them, marriage was about clearly defined roles, familial obligation, and continuity.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">If one were to ask my mother-in-law if she was happy in her marriage, she wouldn’t even understand where that question was coming from.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Her marriage was not about being the wife of a specific person; it was about being a wife in a very general sense—fulfilling a role and a duty.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">As someone who grew up looking to be seen as an individual and loved as an individual, this idea of rigid, clearly-defined roles has been very painful for me (the part that goes like this:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">hi, we just met and I don’t know you or anything about you, but I’ve decided that you are going to act like this and what relationship we’re going to have, and no, you don’t have say in this, so bend over and touch my feet), but perhaps I will write about that later.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">We really do learn our ideas about marriage, love, and romance from what we see as children, so I’m stuck wondering how this has affected our marriage.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Even if my husband knows something intellectually, what he saw as a child has probably been behind many of our fights and resentments.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">Things I see as major problems in a marriage don’t seem like major problems to him.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFCC;">I wonder if we hurt each other because, at the end of the day, we’ve internalized different ideas of what marriage is all about.</span><span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-121692389134435022?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/05/may-alien-world-view.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-07-14T09:56:37.993-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:94:"http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S_F6iXdleeI/AAAAAAAAADg/Dtl0EEPTsJk/s72-c/spock_tpau.jpg";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"12";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:12;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-7745980930521975214";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sun, 25 Apr 2010 17:59:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:8:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Interfaith";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Christian";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"arranged marriage";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Catholic";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Culture";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"Hindu";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:6;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Identity";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:7;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"food";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"Religion, Culture, and Identity (All in One Post!)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14782:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9SD4pd4RGI/AAAAAAAAADY/6NzXvpER4UM/s1600/DSC_0037.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9SD4pd4RGI/AAAAAAAAADY/6NzXvpER4UM/s400/DSC_0037.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5464137257134343266" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="mso-bidi-mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin;font-family:Calibri;color:#333333;">[</span><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Note:</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">This post may seem a little half-baked, as it’s more “maybe this is why…” than anything else, but it’s something I’ve been wrestling with a great deal lately]. Unlike my husband, whose family has lived in Maharashtra for hundreds upon hundreds of years, I don’t have straight-up ethnicity.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I have ancestors from more than eight countries.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">If I have anything like an ethnicity, it’s Catholicism.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">And I think that part of my reluctance to part to with it is that it feels like losing the sense of culture.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">When one of those lecture uncles gives me the “India is better than America because we have culture and tradition and you don’t” speeches (I’m sure you’ve heard that one.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">SRK’s speech in Swades made me so happy), I have always had Catholicism.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">This morning I was reading a New Yorker article about the ordination of women as bishops in the Church of England.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">As I was reading it, I wondered how I could be sitting here rooting for the ordination of female bishops in the C of E but still feel a strong pull towards remaining Catholic.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I know, it’s ridiculous and irrational.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I want women to have a stronger role and more equality in Catholicism.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">The Anglicans already HAVE it.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">The more I read about the ugliness of my home church’s cover-up of child molestation, the more I question my desire to stay.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">My husband does not understand at all.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">He basically thinks I have Stockholm syndrome.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">At this point, I might even want to concede that point with the caveat that I still question whether it is appropriate for the angry, hurt, pissed off Catholics to just throw up our hands and leave the Roman Catholic Church.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">                </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">At this point, I despise much of the administration of the Catholic Church, but what is it that keeps me clinging?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">What is it that makes me want to be back in those pews saying those words?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">How much of it has to do with God and how much of it has to do with culture?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Am I scared of going WASP?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Is that my problem?</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I’m only half-joking when I say that.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">So much of my life and my thinking has been informed by a particularly Catholic mindset and Catholic culture that I can’t help but hurt a little bit when I think about losing it.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Maybe it’s silly, but I feel like it’s a huge part of who I am.<o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">                </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">They say that you are what you defend (which would make me really Desi…total tangent).</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">As a child growing up in a predominantly fundamentalist Christian town (though that’s changing a bit), my siblings and I had to defend ourselves against playground evangelists.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">You know what I mean, the kids who go up to other kids on the playground and say, “Have you asked Jesus into your heart?” and then tell you that you aren’t really a Christian and that you’re a cannibal.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I grew up having to defend Catholicism tooth and nail.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I think that even if I do start going to another church for spiritual reasons, I will always defend Catholicism against those fallacious and oh-so-common attacks from fundamentalists.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">                </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Also, Catholicism does provide one with certain privileges.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I’m talking about a sense of belonging.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I certainly don’t fit in well with most groups (I never have), so I’ve always treasured the sense of belonging I get from being able to say, “I’m Catholic.”</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">When I’m together we can bond over shared experiences.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Being Catholic also comes with a culture.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">We’re Irish and Italian and Mexican and Filipino and everything else.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">We drink—a lot.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">We have specific food for specific saint’s days and feasts.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">We have a bunch of holidays other people don’t have. We have homemade first communion dresses and special cakes and bread to eat on Ephiphany. I always enjoyed celebrating those days and their accompanying food, and that’s something I want to pass on to my kids when I have them. I’ve always enjoyed the cultural part of things, but I guess I don’t necessarily have to get rid of that stuff (well, except for the first communion dresses) if I go over to another church.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I don’t necessarily believe some of the stuff that comes with Catholic culture.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Some of it is downright funny.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I happen to know that my mom buried a statue of St. Joseph upside down in the yard to try to sell the house.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">That’s just superstition.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I want to be free of the superstitious stuff, but I admit I’ve grown used to certain things and don’t find them as bizarre as someone coming from an outside perspective might.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I think that much of Hinduism is the same—many of the practices are cultural, not religious, but they are continued as though they actually have something to do with God.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;"><o:p></o:p></span></span></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span style="font-family:Calibri;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Yes, I know that if I start going to an Anglican church that doesn’t mean I’ve changed religions, but it is still a big deal culturally.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I was reading somewhere about ex-Mormon support groups (no offense intended at all, Dugi—I’m just drawing a parallel!).</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">My husband couldn’t understand why anyone would need an ex-Mormon support group.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">I understood completely.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">By leaving that particular church, they were pulling away from the traditions of their families and the strong sense of community they had grown up with.</span><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">  </span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFCCCC;">Maybe they had found a way to understand God in that was the truth for them and that provided the answers that they personally were looking for, or found a place that made them feel more accepted for whatever reason, but they still mourned for the good bits.</span><span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-7745980930521975214?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:86:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/religion-culture-and-identity-all-in.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-07-14T09:58:00.813-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9SD4pd4RGI/AAAAAAAAADY/6NzXvpER4UM/s72-c/DSC_0037.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"11";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:13;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-1182662414180718693";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 24 Apr 2010 20:13:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"immigration";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"green card";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"marriage";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:25:"The Green Card Experience";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20117:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9O0xdKUM0I/AAAAAAAAADI/yDTJe0UP5Q8/s1600/DSC_0033.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9O0xdKUM0I/AAAAAAAAADI/yDTJe0UP5Q8/s400/DSC_0033.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5463909534665028418" /></a><br /><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">I</span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"> actually wrote this a while ago after our actual green card interview (a fun thing that took us a year and a half to get).  We were successful, but the process was confusing, stressful, and oh, yeah, really freaking expensive).  Based on our experience, I wrote up my idea of what the USCIS job posting must look like:</span></span><div><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></div><div><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:normal"><span class="apple-style-span"><span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">Hey, Are You A Douche Bag? Want to make a Career out of it? Apply to USCIS!</span></span></span></span></span><span style="Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;font-family:&quot;;font-size:12.0pt;color:#333333;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">Are you known among your close friends and family as a douche bag? Do you take great pleasure in having power over others? Would you describe yourself as anal retentive, controlling, and compulsively bureaucratic? As a child, did you enjoy capturing animals and then shaking the jar and seeing if they would fight? Has a psychiatric professional ever suggested that you have a “God complex” or “narcissistic personality disorder?” If so, you have the qualities we’re looking for at US Customs and Immigration. If you think you have what it takes, please send in your replies to the following questions along with the other items listed at the bottom of this post.</span></span></span></span><span class="apple-converted-space"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"> </span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">Answer each of the following questions about the scenario described. Explain your answer in exactly one hundred words and fax it separately. Each answer must have its own cover sheet. The cover sheet must include your full name, address, and the job posting number. We will not provide a fax number for you to send it to. Do not call or e-mail us to obtain the fax number.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">Scenario 1:</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">A couple comes into the office for their green card sponsorship interview. They have their lawyer with them. They have filed all paperwork on time and have paid all fees. They brought two full binders worth of evidence in addition to copies to all documents they have already filed. Everything appears to be in order. The couple takes out their passports, tax returns, driver’s licenses and current lease. The lease indicates that they moved six weeks ago. One member of the couple has not had his/her driver’s license updated to the new address yet. The license will not expire for another year. In this situation, how do you make the interviewees as uncomfortable as possible?</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">A) I would talk to the couple as though they are children about the need to update the license</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">B) I will insinuate that the un-updated license is grounds when rejection and then pretend to look something up while actually checking my facebook</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">C) I will make off-color jokes indicating that the spouse with the updated license should have found a way to illegally obtain an updated license for his/her spouse and is therefore an inadequate spouse because he/she did not try to commit fraud</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">D) None of the above. I might suggest a trip to the DMV after the green card comes through (thereby saving lots of paperwork for the DMV and USCIS), but as long as the license is unexpired and I have other forms of identification available, it’s not worth wasting time on.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">E) A-C</span></span></span></span><span class="apple-converted-space"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"> </span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">If you answered E to the question above, please move on to the next question. If you answered D, please destroy all copies of your application.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">Scenario 2:</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">A couple has submitted all paperwork and fees for a green card sponsorship. They’ve come into your office with additional evidence, copies of all previously submitted paperwork, and a lawyer. You can find no reason to deny their application. In the file, you see a previously submitted application for an employment green card. How can you derive the most pleasure out of this experience?</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">A) I would get the most pleasure out of simply telling them that their application had been approved. I would not enjoy keeping them in suspense any longer than necessary.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">B) I would sit and look at the older application for a long time and repeatedly mumble, “Wait a minute…” while the couple looked on in fear. For extra fun, I might leave the room for a minute with the form, walk to the break room, see if anyone brought in any donuts, check my facebook, call my cousin, and then return to the interview room and announce that their application has been approved.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">C) I will repeatedly question the sponsoring spouse about the details of the previous application, all the while insinuating that the new application is a case of fraud.</span></span></span></span><span class="apple-converted-space"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"> </span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">D) I will take out the old application, stare at it for a while, and then say “I am going to recommend that you withdraw your application.” I will look up at the terrified couple and relish the look of fear on their faces for a few seconds before I say, “Because this application is being approved.”</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">E) I would not derive any pleasure out of approving an application. If I could not find a way out of approving the card, I would find a way to make them return for a second interview.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">If you answered B, C, D, or E please move on to the next question. If you answered A, please shred your application and place the shredded material in an 8 by 11 inch padded envelope and mail it to the department of Homeland Security.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">Please answer the following questions with “yes” or “no”:</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">1) It is appropriate to lie or make false claims about green card eligibility if the applicant does not have a lawyer in the room.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">2) It is appropriate to ask applicants about their sex lives for my own enjoyment.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">3) If I already have several copies of a document in front of me, I should ask the applicants for another copy.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">4) I enjoy the order and neatness that mindless redundant bureaucracy brings about</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">5) A US birth certificate, thirty years of tax records, a US passport, and thirty years of voting records are not sufficient evidence of US Citizenship for an applicant’s parent</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">6) I enjoy having power over others. It makes up for my own inner sense of failure.</span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /></span></span></span><span class="apple-style-span"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;">If you answered “yes” to all of the above, please submit four copies of your resume, proof of US citizenship, a processing fee of fifty dollars, answers to the KSAs listed on the USAjobs.gov website under job listing 349FTZ—GS-9, a letter of recommendation, and five references by mail, fax, and e-mail (PDF format) by tomorrow. If all parts of your application are not received by the close of business tomorrow, you will be subject to a full investigation.</span></span></span></span><span class="apple-converted-space"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"> </span></span></span></span><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="color:#FFFFFF;"><span class="Apple-style-span"  style="font-family:verdana;"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: small;"><br /><br /></span></span></span><br /></span><span style="Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;font-family:&quot;;font-size:12.0pt;"></span><o:p></o:p></p></div><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-1182662414180718693?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:71:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/green-card-experience.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-24T20:21:05.778-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9O0xdKUM0I/AAAAAAAAADI/yDTJe0UP5Q8/s72-c/DSC_0033.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"6";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:14;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-7080048011248003191";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 22 Apr 2010 16:42:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"India";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:24:"generational differences";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"Goodness Gracious Me";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Odd Lectures from Cranky Uncles";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8523:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9B_RqVyhSI/AAAAAAAAADA/qpf-9k278gA/s1600/DSC_0029.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9B_RqVyhSI/AAAAAAAAADA/qpf-9k278gA/s400/DSC_0029.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5463006289400595746" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">             </span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">   </span>Ok, I know that it happens to everyone, but that doesn’t make it any easier to take.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Friends of mine have come back from Mexico, France, and Thailand with tales of it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve sat through various versions of it in India and at desi parties here in the U.S.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m sure you’ve been on the receiving end of it, or at least heard someone else take it, at one time or another.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>What am I talking about?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Why, the good old fashioned anti-Western lecture of course!<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve had to sit through long, insulting, patronizing lectures on why arranged marriage is better than other types of marriage, lectures on how America is destroying the world with its liberalism, and, my personal favorite, why western women are so much worse than Indian women (anything “wrong” with Indian women, is, surprise, surprise, the fault of Western influence).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve received these lectures from guests in my own home.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve also been given these lectures as an invited guest in someone home.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Generally, the person who gives one of these lectures is a man who is fifty or older and who is not used to being contradicted.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>And generally, not being a saint or a martyr, I come away from these lectures steamed.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Probably the worst one I’ve heard was at the house a Jain man whom I’ll refer to as the multi-millionaire.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The multi-millionaire invited us into his house (three floors of an apartment building).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Underneath the house were his three Mercedes Benzes.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The multi-millionaire made his money working for a European pharmaceutical corporation.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>His sons were away in Germany studying, but their wives were living with him and his wife.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After telling us (my husband and I) in a back-handed way that our marriage was doomed to fail because I was obviously the scum of the earth, he began dissing all Indians who leave India (I’m not sure how his sons didn’t fall into that category).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>As obnoxious as it was to hear a man with a four-foot high portrait of himself telling us about the beauty of the lives of the poor in India (who, according to him, want for nothing), the worst part came when he started insulting his daughter-in-law, who, by the way, was there in the room.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Look at her,” he said, pointing at the college-educated woman, who, by the way was six months pregnant with his grandchild, “she does nothing.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“I’m sure you do I lot of things,” I said, looking at her.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She tried to laugh it off.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The multi-millionaire said patronizing things like, “Gandhi—I doubt you’ve heard of him…” (yes, he actually said that, Americans are all very stupid, you see).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>He finished up his lecture by telling us how all Indians were into peace, harmony, and love.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Attributes he clearly personified.  I gulped down a lot of tea to keep myself quiet while he talked.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes"></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>There have been others, some more obnoxious than others.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I try my best to endure them, but I hate the part where I have to touch their feet when it’s time to go.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I suppose it’s an exercise in great humility to take it and then bend down and touch their feet, but as I said before, I am neither a saint nor a martyr.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My husband and I had a little tiff last night because one a friend’s parents are coming to town for six month visit beginning at the end of this month.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My past encounters with the father have not gone well.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If I’m sitting at a dinner table with him, he, like a kid with a bb-gun shooting at an animal in a cage, comes at me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Because of the way this man expects to be treated (in his case:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I talk, you sit there and shut up), everyone, including my husband and my friends, just sit there and let him have at me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>There is no room for conversation, dialogue, or debate in his reality.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I am supposed to listen quietly and not talk back:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>the relationship of a child to an adult rather than of two adults.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After a one such lecture, I slipped into the kitchen to find his daughter-in-law.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Don’t let it get to you,” she told me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“He’s a blowhard.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I want to try to avoid having to get any more lectures from him. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>My husband has promised to help me avoid exposure to him and to help intervene when the pellets start flying in my direction.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I wonder why people feel the need to do this.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I suppose insecurity is the main reason.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They are used to things being one way (Maharastrian Brahmin marries Maharashtrian Brahmin and lives out his live in Maharashtra speaking Marathi), so when they see me or my husband, they feel that the order they have always believed in has been upset.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Perhaps they see themselves as losing power and feel that the only way to bolster their own egos is to knock down someone else’s—even if that person is a twenty-something year old nobody.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>And though it makes no sense to attack me and blame me for the mistakes or foibles of my home country (or in some cases, other people’s home countries), I am a convenient punching bag.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I sometimes wonder how they feel when they are done.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Do they really feel like they’ve triumphed over me and my nasty heathen ways and shown how truly superior they are? </p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I’d like to know hear how others have dealt with these tirades.</p><p class="MsoNormal">P.S. Here are some videos from Goodness Gracious Me of the "everything is Indian" uncle.  Enjoy:</p><p class="MsoNormal">-<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zfpqfwt_cLg&amp;feature=related">Queen of England, Indian</a></p><p class="MsoNormal">-<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=olF4kpkiWys">Hollywood Stars, Indian</a></p><p class="MsoNormal">-<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hjWd9a8Ck8U&amp;feature=fvw">Leonardo DaVinci, Indian</a></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-7080048011248003191?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/odd-lectures-from-cranky-uncles.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-22T09:55:48.205-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9B_RqVyhSI/AAAAAAAAADA/qpf-9k278gA/s72-c/DSC_0029.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"24";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:15;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-2030048082442172682";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 21 Apr 2010 18:06:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"India";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Hinduism";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Star Trek";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Hippies";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"Hippies, Hinduism, and Captain Picard";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10515:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S88_Apozh4I/AAAAAAAAAC4/RhGjx5PkYf4/s1600/DSC_9983.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S88_Apozh4I/AAAAAAAAAC4/RhGjx5PkYf4/s400/DSC_9983.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5462654153433253762" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">I’ve never known what to think of Westernized versions of Hinduism. One way a person could think of it is that it’s just another aspect of multi-culturalism—people being open to a variety of religious traditions.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>One could also think about it as profoundly disrespectful.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It could be seen as appropriation, or as a friend of mine recently put it, “using other people’s religion or culture as a playground for rich white people."<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Most Indians I know openly mock Westerners who take on Eastern religions (Buddhism, Hinduism, Sikhism).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At the recent cocktail party, an Indian acquaintance started telling a story about seeing a “white sardar” at an airport.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“The guy had a bright orange beard,” the storyteller laughed.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But, of course, somebody else managed to top that story by telling us about seeing a “black sardar.” </p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in"><span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>I think that part of the strangeness comes from the fact that Hinduism isn’t a big conversion religion.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When we think of Christianity or Islam, we see nothing funny or strange about meeting believers of every race because either the person or his or her ancestors converted to that religion.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Most Hindus and Sikhs were born into their religion and don’t really go around trying to convert others to it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I could conjecture about why so many Westerners flock to Hinduism, as well as why so many Hindus dislike such people, but I’d rather tell you a funny story.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>(Well, I hope it’s funny.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At a minimum, it’s bizarre):</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I got my first taste of Americanized Hinduism in a room above a garage in the Midwest.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I ended up there out of curiosity; I had read an old Dover edition of the Bhagavad Gita and, since I’ve always liked religion and been curious about it, I got in a car with some other teenagers and headed out to into the county.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I actually don’t remember what I was expecting.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At that time in my life, I think I anticipated a transcendental experience around every corner (not so these days), so I probably hoped to feel something.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>After about twenty minutes on country roads, we pulled into a long dirt driveway.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We parked and then walked up to the top of the hill, where we found a house and a strange, two-story garage with swimming-pool sized satellite dish attached to it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>One of the girls, who had been to the place before, took us around back to a metal door.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We entered the garage, shimmied past the trucks parked in it, and then removed our shoes at the bottom of a wooden staircase.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At the top of the stairs, we entered a carpeted room full of white Mid-westerners.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The walls were decked out in color photos of various gurus.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Everyone was facing a four-foot-high photo of an Indian guru.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We took our seats on the floor and waited.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Now, when I say these people were “hippies,” keep in mind that I’m a vegetarian with a deep love of home-grown tomatoes, recycling bins, and compost piles.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So believe me when I tell you there was some crunchy granola in that room.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Once everyone had arrived, a person in charge started playing a CD of chants.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I like singing and chanting with people—the feeling of being a part of a joyful noise, even if my own voice isn’t lovely on its own.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Singing and chanting bring people together in a creative act that is both calming and exhilarating.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Knowing the words makes you feel included.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In the spirit of being curious, I listened for a few minutes until I could make out the words and then joined in the singing. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>I enjoyed the singing in the same way that I enjoyed singing at Mass, or at youth group, or around the campfire with friends.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It was good to be part of the song, even if I was unsure what I was saying.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The chanting, like the chanting done by Christians and Buddhists, left me calm and helped me to focus.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Whether I felt any stirring the divine, I was unsure, but the chanting, in and of itself, was surely good for my unhappy teenaged mind.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So far, I could see what appealed to hanging out above a garage with middle-aged men with unconventional personal hygiene habits.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Then, as John Berryman would say, came the departure.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The CD came to an end and the person in charge, a middle-aged woman, got up and started talking about their guru.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For only $35.00 per person, we could come to a special world-wide satellite broadcast of the guru himself chanting.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Ok, I thought, trying to continue to give this place the benefit of the doubt.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It probably costs a lot of money for them to maintain that big satellite dish, I thought as she offered a CD set, booklet, and video tape up for sale.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I didn’t let that bother me so much as I grew up with the annual bishop’s appeal and PBS fundraising week.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>What bothered me most was what came next.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The woman took out a square of carpet from a wooden box and placed a pair of sandals on it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The square of carpet, she told us, came from the actual meditation chamber of the actual guru.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Some of the audience oh-ed and ah-ed as she placed it in on the floor under the guru’s photo.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The woman then invited us to meditate silently while thinking of the guru.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She told us that after we had finished our meditation, we could come up and touch the square of carpet, either with our heads or our hands, and then we were free to leave money if we wanted to.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I waited for a minute, out of politeness, and then headed back down into the garage.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I put my boots back on and wandered around outside for a little while.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>What had I been thinking coming here?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>How could I have been so stupid?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I heard someone in the woods behind me shouting, “Bhima!<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Bhima!”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I turned around and saw a yellow lab bounding towards me out of the pines.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>An eighteen or nineteen year-old guy was chasing after him with a leash.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Bhima came over to me, tail wagging, and let me pet him.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Are you a naughty boy, Bhima?” I asked him.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Oh you’re a sweetie.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>The boy caught up with Bhima and, winded, asked me if everyone was done upstairs.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Nah,” I said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“They’re still up there.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m just waiting on my friends.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Not your thing, huh?” he said, putting Bhima on his leash.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“It’s more my parents’ thing than mine.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>You can come in the house and wait for your friends.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I followed him into the house, where I sat on the couch with the boy and the dog and watched Star Trek:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The Next Generation on TV.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When I saw my friends leave the garage, I said goodbye and hurried out to the car.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> Driving home in the dark,</span> friends were discussed where they could dig up the cash to go to the satellite broadcast.  Needless to say, I didn't go back.</p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-2030048082442172682?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:85:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/hippies-hinduism-and-captain-picard.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-07-14T10:11:31.288-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S88_Apozh4I/AAAAAAAAAC4/RhGjx5PkYf4/s72-c/DSC_9983.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"14";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:16;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-345613130464879938";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sun, 18 Apr 2010 18:40:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"birding";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"India";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Salim Ali";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:42:"My Steamy Passion for a Dead Ornithologist";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7200:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8tSZ5fWEgI/AAAAAAAAACw/rockaaNr6Cw/s1600/DSC_0041.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8tSZ5fWEgI/AAAAAAAAACw/rockaaNr6Cw/s400/DSC_0041.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5461549577999356418" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">Back when we were just dating, my husband took a trip back home to India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In addition to a couple of salwar kameezes, he brought me a hardback copy of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salim_Ali_(ornithologist)">Salim Ali</a>’s The <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Book-Indian-Birds-Salim-Ali/dp/0195665236/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1271616266&amp;sr=8-1">Book of Indian Birds</a>.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That book, though it’s now a bit outdated, has been my best friend every time we go to India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve always loved animals, and few things give me more glee than spotting a rare bird up in the canopy.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My copy of The Book of Indian Birds has helped me start conversations, kept me occupied when during the long stretches of boredom the come with every trip to India, helped me look busy when needed, and allowed me to communicate with non-English speakers.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Hanging out in my husband’s home town in Maharashtra is boring.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Profoundly boring.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I can’t go anywhere or do anything on my own while there, and if I so much as wander down into the little parking lot of the apartment complex, all the neighbors stick their heads out to stare at me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I do a lot of reading in India, but, when my eyes are tired of the printed page, I lean out the windows, careful not to touch the dusty grills, and watch for birds.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Even in the big city, I’ve had the good fortune to see <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red-whiskered_Bulbul">Red-Whiskered Bulbuls</a> and <a href="http://www.walkthewilderness.net/2009/03/birding-in-india-white-browed-fantail.html">Fantail Flycatchers</a> taking advantage of the cool parts of the morning.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Even on the dullest day, or while stuck with the most agonizingly patronizing tea-time visitor, the activities of birds outside the window provide me with relief.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My field-guide has helped me break the ice with dozens of relatives and tea-time visitors.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Often, when my mother-in-law’s friends or relatives come over to her apartment, they sit across from me, their tea getting cold in the tiny china cups, and stare at me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Many of them have never been in close proximity to a non-Indian before and have no idea what to do with me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Also, many of them only speak Marathi, rendering my broken Hinglish useless.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Busting out Salim Ali is always a way to break the ice.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I just take out the book and start pointing out the birds I’ve seen lately.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They can then start showing me the birds they normally see, or their favorite birds, and the proverbial ice is broken.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The beauty of a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Avadavat">Green Munia</a> or <a href="http://orientalbirdimages.org/birdimages.php?action=birdspecies&amp;Bird_ID=857&amp;Bird_Image_ID=995">Black Baza</a> transcends all the barriers of language, nationality, or culture. </p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>There are <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Birds-Pakistan-Bangladesh-Bhutan-Maldives/dp/0691049106/ref=pd_cp_b_2">more recent field guides</a> to Indian, Sri Lankan, and Pakistani bird species now available, but all of them owe their existence to Salim Ali.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Ali was a peculiar man whose unorthodox methods often bothered his colleagues.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Still, he is a lion-like figure in Indian natural history and conservation circles.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>One of my favorite memories in India was a guide-led trek through a preserve in south India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The guide, one of those amazing people who can tell you the species of a bird from a single note sung a mile away, saw me flipping through my Salim Ali field guide and was very impressed.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“This book is now a little outdated,” he told me, showing me a bird whose scientific name has recently been updated.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“But we consider this book our Bible.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It’s absolutely the Bible.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My field guide is a record of my time spent in India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Next to each species I’ve seen, I’ve written in the date and place I saw the bird.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I can go back and look at a species and remember exactly where I first saw it and how excited I was.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>(“Aha!<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>January 8<sup>th</sup>, 2008!<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That was five <a href="http://www.ecoindia.com/animals/birds/common-kingfisher.html">kingfisher</a> day!”)<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I suppose, in some ways, looking for birds is a kind of collecting, though what I collect is a memory rather than an object.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Looking out for a new species gives me a small but badly needed sense of purpose when I’m in India and feel helpless to do anything.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I open up my field guide, and I look at all the birds I’ve seen, all the birds I still want to see, and all the places I still need to go.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I am grateful to Salim Ali for all his careful records, and I am grateful for every bird who has been so kind as to sit still for my binoculars and let me take in its beauty.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-345613130464879938?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:76:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/my-steamy-passion-for-dead.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-18T11:57:26.733-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8tSZ5fWEgI/AAAAAAAAACw/rockaaNr6Cw/s72-c/DSC_0041.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"3";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:17;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-1451188426168813396";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 17 Apr 2010 16:18:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:""What, You're a Vegetarian?"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7157:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8nf6mFsUxI/AAAAAAAAACo/MNsdyrY9oCY/s1600/DSC_0027.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8nf6mFsUxI/AAAAAAAAACo/MNsdyrY9oCY/s400/DSC_0027.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5461142220913267474" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">“Do not marry a Muslim.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Do not marry a Christian.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Do not marry someone who is not from Maharashtra.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>And do not marry a non-vegetarian.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Those are the guidelines my husband’s aunts gave him for finding a wife.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Well, I’m not from Maharashtra, and I am a Christian, but, hey, I happen to be a non-Muslim who is also a vegetarian.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in">“Are you an Indian vegetarian or an American vegetarian?” the forty-something Gujurati man asked me from across the table.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I had just met this guy and he seemed uncomfortable with me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I searched my brain’s data files for information on vegetarianism in each of the two countries.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I knew that some Hindus choose not to eat mushrooms, and I knew that Jains traditionally do not eat vegetables grown underground.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In terms of the US, was he talking about vegans, perhaps?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>People all over the world can be very defensive about eating habits (i.e. Thanksgiving at my grandparents’ house:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Hey kid, you enjoying yer damn rabbit food?” and don’t get me started on the perils of having to answer the “So, why are you a vegetarian?” question—ugh, that’s a different post), so I tried not to sound combative when I asked “What’s an ‘American vegetarian?’”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“An American vegetarian,” he informed me with great authority, “eats chicken and fish.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Unsure where he got his information, I made a quizzical face. “That’s not a vegetarian,” I said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“That’s someone who is lying of delusional,” I laughed.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Luckily, putting some humor into the situation defused any awkwardness. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>“I’m an ovo-lacto vegetarian,” I explained.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“That’s the most common type here.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I eat eggs and milk—animal products that don’t require killing an animal--but there are also vegetarians here who do not eat dairy, eggs, or honey.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>People all over the world define the term ‘vegetarian’ differently.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In some Indian households, eggs are taboo (explanation:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“eggs are not a vegetable”—very true!).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But in other households, especially in coastal areas, fish are considered vegetarian.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve even heard an old south Indian auntie call fish “fruit from the sea.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>This is very similar to the old “fish on Fridays” tradition in Christianity.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>As far as I can tell, finding a strict definition of “Indian vegetarian” is just as impossible as finding a definition of an “American vegetarian.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Take a look at Sathya Srinavasan’s <a href="http://cssathya.blogspot.com/2010/03/what-indian-vegetarian-are-you.html">chart</a> (which is a bit tongue in cheek, considering that it includes cannibals) for more definitions of vegetarianism in India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My husband, who is a Hindu, started eating meat (chicken and fish) as an adult.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I stopped eating meat as a teenager.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Indians, both here and in India, are often extremely surprised to find out that I am a vegetarian, and often probe me with skeptical questions to try to see if I am actually a vegetarian.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When they find out that I am they are even more shocked.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Some people even seem to refuse to believe it no matter how many times they see me eat.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For example, once when I was mixing up a batch of falafel, my mother in law came and asked my husband if I was making chicken.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Doesn’t she believe that I’m a vegetarian?” I asked my husband.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Well, you know.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>This has happened more than once, to my chagrin.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>On the other hand, some Hindus consider me, and my mother-in-law, non-veg because we both eat eggs.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>While on the elderly Maharashtrian ladies tour of the Andaman Islands, one older auntie found it necessary to make disparaging remarks about our eating “non-veg” omelets from the buffet table.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After she complained to the tour guide, those of us who ate eggs were relegated to a separate table. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Those of us at the egg eaters were able to bond a little over being singled out as somehow unclean.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Still, being a vegetarian (well, some people’s idea of a vegetarian!) has helped me to get some older Indians to soften to me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When they learn that I, the foreigner, do something that even many Marathi “manoos” don’t do, they can start to see me less in terms of stereotypes about the west and more in terms of being an individual who has thought through her own choices. </p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-1451188426168813396?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:71:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/what-youre-vegetarian.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-17T09:22:08.203-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8nf6mFsUxI/AAAAAAAAACo/MNsdyrY9oCY/s72-c/DSC_0027.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"15";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:18;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-6077622775788877147";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 14 Apr 2010 22:43:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"blogging";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:42:"Hoping This Blog is Bigger Than "ME ME ME"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3598:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8ZFlaBXtRI/AAAAAAAAACg/yekgkMS9W-k/s1600/DSC_9971.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8ZFlaBXtRI/AAAAAAAAACg/yekgkMS9W-k/s400/DSC_9971.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5460128107175851282" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">In undergrad and grad school, I often needed to write an Ars Poetica (justification of writing poetry, written in verse) at the end of each semester’s writing workshop.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It was a useful exercise in many ways, as it required me to really examine what mattered to me in the work I was doing.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I think I want to do the same thing, briefly, for this blog (an Ars Blogica?).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Last night, somebody important to me made a disparaging comment about my desire to keep this blog.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Are you looking for people to feel sorry for you?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Isn’t this just ‘Waah, look what I’ve been through?’” person X asked.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The answer is no.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I don’t want anyone to feel sorry for me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I would prefer that people thought I was tough.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">   </span>But the question made me want to lay out some of my reasons for doing this and what I hope this “project” can yield.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">It’s no secret that the nature of the blogosphere is narcissistic.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Well, duh.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Every act of writing is, to a certain extent, narcissistic.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>One of my favorite poetry teachers once told me that when we write poems, we are asking the reader to fall in love with us.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>And I believe that, beloved reader.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But what about this blog? I hope that what I write here is about more than just me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When I write about my experiences, I am trying to create meaning from them.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>What use is pain if you can’t find meaning in it, learn something from it (even if it is something you’d prefer not to learn, like how selfish you can be), or find some humor buried somewhere in it?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That is what I aim to do.  Try to make sense of my experience and make it into something meaningful to more than just me. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>I’ve only been doing this for nine days, but I’ve been enjoying it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It guarantees that I write every day, it gives me a place to formulate my thoughts on important topics through writing, and, most importantly, it has introduced me to people who have had similar experiences or know more than I do.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That feels like enough.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I hope it is.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-6077622775788877147?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:87:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/hoping-this-blog-is-bigger-than-me-me.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-14T15:48:52.207-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8ZFlaBXtRI/AAAAAAAAACg/yekgkMS9W-k/s72-c/DSC_9971.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"6";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:19;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-7402239209155613387";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 14 Apr 2010 22:32:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"India";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:24:"generational differences";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"waitress";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"cultural differences";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:19:"That Waitress Thing";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5420:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9PCpEA8xlI/AAAAAAAAADQ/oc63E2gW8Fs/s1600/DSC_0030.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9PCpEA8xlI/AAAAAAAAADQ/oc63E2gW8Fs/s400/DSC_0030.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5463924783638693458" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormalCxSpFirst" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">There are many common domestic practices that I have adjusted to or learned to understand while at my MIL's house.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But the waitress thing is not one of them.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>What am I talking about?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Well, when we’re in India, and occasionally when we’re in an Indian or Pakistani American household here, we sit down at the table along with all the men, while the women congregate in the kitchen.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Then, the women come to the table bearing bowls of food and serve everyone.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Then, as soon as you’ve finished anything on your plate, they scramble to replace it with more.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Only when everyone else is finished eating will they have any food.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>This makes me extremely uncomfortable for obvious reasons.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">I’m not just uncomfortable because I have to defend my plate from the caloric influx with one hand while eating with the other (“Bas!<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Bas!”), I’m uncomfortable with the division of labor by gender.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> This even happens in the homes of friends of mine who are my age or a little older.  Though they may not think it's right, they go along with it anyway.  </span>I’ve heard people defend this gender separation by saying that it gives the women a chance to get together and talk to their friends.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>To this I say, huh, couldn’t they get together and talk just as easily in a sitting position, with, say, a cup of tea?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>And what if a woman wanted to have a conversation with a man?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">The other argument I’ve heard is that the waitress thing is a way to show love.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“They don’t know any other way to show affection,” I’ve been told.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“They are old desi aunties.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Food is their only vehicle for expressing positive emotions.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That’s probably true.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That and buying stuff! </p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">I grew up with a family that ate dinner together most nights of the week.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Everyone chipped-in in their own small way—either setting the table or clearing it and washing the dishes after the meal.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My mom cooked, but so did my dad.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Family meals were a time to say grace together, talk about school, and enjoy each other’s company.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The idea of eating while one member of the family is toiling away is, well, completely foreign to me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">One of my Indian friends, however, put an end to her mother’s waitress behavior when she was about thirteen.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She and her brother both tried to explain to their mom that they didn’t like it when she waited on them.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They wanted her at the table with them.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Their mom countered that she only did it so they could have hot chapattis.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The mom finally acquiesced when both kids and their dad decided they would wait to eat until the mom sat down.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>Since then, their mom has always sat with them at the table. </p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">I suppose the waitress thing gives the aunties a sense of power and control in a way—nobody eats anything unless they bring it and everybody has to eat what they bring.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It probably brings them some measure of satisfaction that they otherwise don’t get to experience.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  Also, many women of my own generation eschew this practice and eat with their families.   </span>Still, it’s not something I can see myself getting used to.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-7402239209155613387?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/that-waitress-thing.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-11-07T12:58:04.825-08:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S9PCpEA8xlI/AAAAAAAAADQ/oc63E2gW8Fs/s72-c/DSC_0030.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"17";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:20;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-7296097686662128908";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 14 Apr 2010 03:22:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"India";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"mother-in-laws";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"A Short Recap of Some Ancient History:  Meeting the MIL for the First Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12251:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://www.globallyminded.com/Blog/files/page12_blog_entry76_4.jpg"><img style="float:right; margin:0 0 10px 10px;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 200px; height: 200px;" src="http://www.globallyminded.com/Blog/files/page12_blog_entry76_4.jpg" border="0" alt="" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">Note: I’m calling my husband “Mr. 4B” (i.e. “Mr. BigBadBlondeBahu”) for this post</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>“My mom will love you.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She’ll love that you’re smart and that you write and paint.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When I’m away at work, you can take her around to museums and you can come back to the apartment and sit on the balcony and hold hands.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">This is what my husband sincerely believed would happen when his mother came to the U.S. for the first time.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It was 2006.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I had just turned twenty-one and had just finished by junior year of college.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After more than two years as a secret, Mr. 4B finally told his mother about me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Now that she was coming to the U.S. for a visit, I had a chance to meet her.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I took an overnight train into town, the same overnight train I so often took to come and visit Mr. 4B.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>About half an hour before the train reached the station, I went down to the bathroom to change, comb my hair, and wash my face.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I checked myself out in the mirror:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>tidy hair, modest clothes (despite the summer heat), a clean face, and, well, my chubby body. </p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">When we reached the station, I picked out a selection of Gerber daisies and arranged them carefully into a bright little bouquet.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">   </span>Mr. 4B had just bought a car, mostly so he could transport his mother around, and I didn’t know what it would look like.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Standing outside the station in the heat, I reiterated everything Mr. 4B had told me about his mother.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>He told me that she was intelligent, strong, and well-educated.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I extrapolated on what he told me, creating a fantasy woman with whom I would get along: strong, independent, feminist, a cosmopolitan woman of the world who shared my love of literature.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>How could such a woman, the woman Mr. 4B described to me, dislike me?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>When I finally Mr. 4B waiting outside the station, I waved and hurried through the lines of cabs to the car.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Through the tinted glass, I could make out a short, stern-faced woman in the passenger seat.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I smiled and waved at her and then climbed into the backseat.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She did not turn to face me, but I pushed the flowers up to her and said, “Hi!<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>These are for you.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m so happy to finally meet you.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>She did not reply, but after a pause, I continued to talk.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“So, how do you like it here?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Have you been out much?”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>No reply. </p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>I looked to Mr. 4B in the rear view mirror for guidance.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Why wasn’t she replying?</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>“She’s just nervous,” he said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Maybe she can’t understand your accent.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1">                </span>The rest of the car ride was silent.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal">When we got back to the apartment, his mother threw the bouquet down on a chair and stormed out onto the balcony.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Mr. 4B followed, and for the next ten minutes, they yelled at each other in Marathi.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I sat down on my suitcase.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I had been on a train for fourteen hours.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I was sure I didn’t smell great.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My hair was probably dirty, too.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Of course I had been here before, but now that his mother was here, the bedroom was completely off-limits to me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I would be staying on the living room floor with Mr. 4B’s mother for propriety’s sake.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">They continued to shout outside, his mother’s voice occasionally rising up into a high pitched scream.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I couldn’t understand their words, so I tried to pretend their fight wasn’t about me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I picked up the flowers from the chair, unwrapped them from their plastic, and arranged them in a glass.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Mr. 4V came in a few minutes later.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>His mother remained on the balcony.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Through the window, I could see her seated with her arms crossed, pouting in folding chair.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“What’s the matter?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Why were you fighting?”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">He got a glass of water.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“We weren’t fighting.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“It sounded like fighting.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“Well, she—she has some concerns.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“Concerns?”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“About your weight.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">My weight.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve never been thin (hence the ‘big’ in my blog title-I’m a size twelve kind of woman) and my weight is a constant source of misery for me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I gulped and looked away.</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“So that’s what she cares about?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That I’m fat.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She doesn’t want to get to know me or anything?”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I always thought that my weight was the only thing people saw when they looked at me, and now this had confirmed it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“It’s more of a concern.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">“A concern?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>You keep saying that.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She stayed on the balcony for a long time.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I wondered if she hoped she could stay out there until I left.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">Mr. 4B went out to ask her something, and she snapped at him again.</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">After that, after the agonizing days alone with her while Mr. 4B was at the office, I had a different picture of this strange, hunched-over old woman who never smiled.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Smart, but stubborn.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Educated, but insecure and controlling. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>My first tangible example of her controlling behavior came on my first day alone with her.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Smiling, trying to talk to her, and generally trying to forget her outburst the day before, I cooked her breakfast, which she deposited in the trash.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Undeterred, I escorted her around the city to museums, walking slowly to match her pace.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When we were alone together in the apartment, she would mumble in Marathi while glaring at me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>(Sometimes I’m glad we have no common language!)</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">Since then, I’ve learned that my weight was just a cover story for everything else that scared her:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>my nationality, my race, my religion, my lack of caste.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My weight was something she could openly object to out loud in front of her son.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If I didn’t have fat for her to grab between her thumb and forefinger and click her tongue at, she would have found something else, some other smokescreen to use to disapprove of me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Of stupid, naïve, twenty-one year-old me, standing there outside the train station with a handful of flowers, truly believing I could have a good relationship with her.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In hindsight, there was nothing I could have done differently (other than look completely different) to make that first meeting go smoothly, though I’ve certainly made mistakes with her since.</p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">That first visit was, clearly, a blow for me, but I think it was worse for Mr. 4B.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For the first time, he saw the worst side of his mother.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>He knew she was stubborn, tough, and stern, but he did not expect this reaction from her.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At the time, I was far too shocked to really empathize with what his mother was putting him through.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Now, in addition to trying to control my emotions around the MIL, I try to have more sympathy for what my husband endures at her hands.</p><p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal">Related:  <a href="http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/forgiveness-mother-in-laws-and-hanging.html">http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/forgiveness-mother-in-laws-and-hanging.html</a></p><p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:normal"><br /></p>  <p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle" style="line-height:normal"><o:p> </o:p></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-7296097686662128908?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:85:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/short-recap-of-some-ancient-history.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-14T08:49:19.853-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"11";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:21;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-3504113740337986324";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 12 Apr 2010 14:13:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:94:"It Don’t Mean a Thing if You Ain’t Got That Bling Part I:  The Many Uses of a Mangal Sutra";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7398:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://www.radheygoldchain.com/full-images/651036.jpg"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 360px; height: 504px;" src="http://www.radheygoldchain.com/full-images/651036.jpg" border="0" alt="" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal">I hand the desi clerk at the grocery store my preferred customer card.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I forgot that my husband put it under his name—a very long, very Indian name.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Mrs. [very-common-Marathi-last-name]?” he asks me skeptically.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Yup, that’s me,” I say, sliding my finger under the black and gold chain of my mangal sutra.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>He hands me back the card and I pay for my order.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My mangal sutra is a necklace that married Hindu women wear across much of India.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  Its name means "auspicious thread, " but </span>I like to call it my Asian street cred.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Mine is fairly inconspicuous, so you might just think that it is a stylized piece of fashion jewelry, but many women wear enormous, almost sculptural, gold and black necklaces every single day.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I’ve tried to find reliable information on the origins and meaning of the mangal sutra, but, like many thing Indian, asking five people about it will yield five contradictory answers.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“It’s Maharashtrian,” I’ve been told.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Only Maharashtrians wear this.” (I’ve learned to take such statements with a full tablespoon of salt, as Maharashtrians will claim that everything is Maharashtrian, the same way that Bengalis like to claim that everything is Bengali, et cetera).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But I know Gujuratis who wear it and Tamils who wear it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Look through the National Geographic gift catalogue, and you will find a Thai version for sale called a Thali (not to be confused with the Indian dinner option).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Many North Indians, however, do not wear it, opting for other jewelry instead.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My little mangalsutra is on a small chain, so I can wear it with relative comfort.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The chain is made of thin links of gold strung through ordinary black beads.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>At the center hang two small half-spheres made of gold.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I have tried to guess at what they represent, and my best guess so far comes from an old mangalsutra I saw at the Smithsonian that was designed around two betel nuts.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ve tried to guess at what the two half-spheres might mean:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>two souls strung together in marriage, perhaps?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If they are stylized betel nuts, what is the significance of two betel nuts?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>All I can do is speculate.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Other anecdotal evidence I’ve been given includes:</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“If you take it off, everyone will assume that your husband is dead.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“Women will wear it even after their husband dies.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“You can never take it off-ever.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“Oh, nobody wears that anymore.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“It has to have two little half-spheres made of gold.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“It can have any kind of pendant as long as the beads are black.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">“It means the same thing whether it is a string with two knots tied in it or if it is inlaid with emeralds and diamonds.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>At first, I didn’t really like the idea of a mangalsutra.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After all, I’m not really a big jewelry person.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I tend to lose things or break things.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Jewelry gets in the way and gets caught on things.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The idea of having a huge chunk of solid gold hanging around my neck on a fragile chain was not exactly appealing.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Also, as a feminist, I dislike the idea of a woman having marriage jewelry but not the man.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Why should a woman be marked as married but not a man?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I wear the mangalsutra as a sort of compromise because we also wear plain, matching wedding bands.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Considering the amount of jewelry my husband’s aunts think I should wear (green bangles, silver toe rings), wearing a small necklace is no big deal to me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Most of my Indian friends don’t wear it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For them, it is a thing of their mothers’ generation.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They don’t need it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>For me, however, as the ferengee in the crowd, it is a sign that I fit in a way.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It’s a pass card.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>In India I also wear it conspicuously to prevent men from bothering me too much.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It acts as a warning sign that says “back off, now.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It also helps a little with older people—the aunties and uncles who find me so threatening.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When they see me with my husband, they generally stare or scowl at me, but when they see the necklace, they often say they like it, which is something.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Not much, but something.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>So, at the end of the day, I can’t tell you what the two little half spheres mean, why the necklace is often made of black beads, or where exactly people do or don’t wear it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Wearing it makes me stand out in some situations, but it also makes me fit a little more in others.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p><p class="MsoNormal">[Note: this photo is from an on-line jewelry store that sells mangal sutras:  radheygoldchain.com]</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-3504113740337986324?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:89:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/it-dont-mean-thing-if-you-aint-got-that.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-12T09:20:13.891-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"17";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:22;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-2277083166434765216";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 12 Apr 2010 01:25:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:74:"Conversation Lost in Translation:  Worship the Tree Like It's Your Husband";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2636:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8J3CMpXJSI/AAAAAAAAACY/NixUIKuP3E4/s1600/DSC_9980.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8J3CMpXJSI/AAAAAAAAACY/NixUIKuP3E4/s400/DSC_9980.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5459056577964614946" /></a><br />This might be the first in a series of short posts.  <div><br /></div><div><p class="MsoNormal">The scene:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>an unpaved road in Maharashtra.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>A herd of goats has just walked by.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“So, when the bangles are nailed to the tree like this, the wife can then worship the tree as the husband.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“What?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I think I missed something.”</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Oh, you see that someone has nailed these green bangles to the tree?”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My husband’s cousin pointed to them as though perhaps I had not seen them.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Someone had, indeed, nailed some green glass bangles to a ficus tree.  I knew that married Maharashtrian women wear green bangles, and that a tree is a perfectly acceptable temple, but I wasn't sure where she was going with this.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“And they have done this as some kind of offering to a specific god?” I asked, hoping she could clarify the point.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“By keeping the bangles on the tree, she can worship it as her husband.”</p><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Apple-tab-span" style="white-space:pre">  </span>I nodded as though I knew what she meant and kept walking, but I couldn't help but wonder.  Did she just lack the vocabulary to express herself, or did she, a woman only a few years older than me, think that women should "worship" their husbands?  Later, I tried asking my husband what his cousin was talking about.  He had no idea either.  </p></div><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-2277083166434765216?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:82:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/conversation-lost-in-translation.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-11T18:36:05.827-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S8J3CMpXJSI/AAAAAAAAACY/NixUIKuP3E4/s72-c/DSC_9980.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"5";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:23;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-7210619132411500328";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 09 Apr 2010 16:15:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"weddings";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"India";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"shoes";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"White Shoes";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13677:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79S6lVqdaI/AAAAAAAAACQ/Y-RqKaz5W5I/s1600/DSC_9974.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79S6lVqdaI/AAAAAAAAACQ/Y-RqKaz5W5I/s400/DSC_9974.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5458172439805195682" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;">When my mother-in-law-to-be called and told my husband that she had gone out and bought thirty saris, including my wedding dress, something in me panicked.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>The part of me that had been thinking “weddings schmeddings, who cares about weddings, they’re ridiculous wastes of resources anyway,” was overcome by a voice saying “Oh shit.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m getting married in a foreign country in a wedding ceremony I’ve only seen in movies and I’ll be dressed up like somebody else’s idea of a bride.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My laid back attitude was beginning to melt away.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Suddenly, I wanted some control. I had heard about other people having fusion ceremonies, half Hindu half Christian, and people having dresses made up from white saris.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>But the people planning this wedding, namely my mother-in-law-to-be and the man we call the dirty uncle, would not allow for such things.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They had not chosen the bride, so nothing was going to stop them from controlling every aspect of the wedding right down to my shoes.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“What does it look like?” I asked my husband.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“What does what look like?”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“The sari.”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“I don’t know.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>It probably has lots of gold on it.”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“And my stomach has to show?”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I said, clutching at the fat paunch sticking out above my jeans.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Knowing my mother-in-law-to-be, I worried the sari would be incredibly tacky.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>During the time she was here, I learned to associate her with cheap plastic doo-dads and Barbie pink polyester, a mix between a tray full of 1950s costume jewelry in a junk store and things a five year old would think were pretty.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Well, I added, “I hope it’s at least made out of materials found in nature.”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>My mother had a white cotton wedding dress.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She made it herself out of the same peasant dress pattern she used to make the calico dresses for the bridesmaids.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My dad wore a used avocado green suit with bell-bottom pants.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They had a grand total of five-hundred dollars to spend on the clothes, the cake, the minister, and the honeymoon.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Though that was worth more in 1973 money, it kept things small, cozy, handmade.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I remembered my mother telling me about a wedding she saw when she was an undergrad living in married student housing.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When one of her Chinese neighbors got married, the bride wore the white bridal dress, but on her feet were bright red shoes: her connection to China, her culture, her memories, herself.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So, in early December, a month before leaving for India, I decided to set out on a search for white shoes.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>It was harder than I thought.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My feet are size 11, usually the largest size any shoe store stocks, though they may have a few pairs of size 12 athletic shoes in the back.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My feet are also incredibly ugly—completely flat with strange ape-like toes, my big toe sticking out like a fat opposable thumb. I wanted my toes covered just like I wanted my stomach covered.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>My soon-to-be-husband complied, driving me to nearly every affordable, and some not so affordable, shoe stores and department stores in the area.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:.5in;line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;">I tend to think of the big city as a place where more things are available, but the plight of the large footed woman seems to be the same everywhere.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I found myself staring at narrow racks of black, brown, or gray office shoes mixed in with running shoes and hiking boots under the sign “Size ten and up.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>There weren’t a lot of “ups,” though I could have gone for a pair of lime green plaid rubber boots at Macy’s for $89.99.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Um, does it have to be white?”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>a teenaged clerk asked.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Can you squeeze into a ten?” another asked, bringing me a pair of gorgeous, snow-white high heels.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Try as I might to squash my feet inside, the answer was no.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“We have ivory penny-loafers over here,” another clerk tried.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>I reverted back to my tried and true shoe-shopping technique.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I would walk into a shoe store, find a clerk, and ask, “Do you carry size 11?”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If the answer was yes, the clerk could then point out the four pairs of shoes I had to choose from.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>If the answer was “no,” I would proclaim in a voice loud enough for all the customers to hear, “Come on honey, they don’t carry my size.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“Well, if you’re wearing a sari, it doesn’t have to be white.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We could go for gold,” a friendly and helpful clerk said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“I know, I just wanted white so I could have something a little bit my culture, you know,” I said.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>She nodded.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She knew what I meant.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>She gave us a list of high-end department stores that might have what I was looking for. <span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We tried H&amp;M, Lord and Taylor, Ann Taylor, Bloomingdales, Nordstrom, Aldo, Nine West, the Jessica McClintock store, and dozens of small shoe shops, Targets, a Sears, three Macy’s, two Penney’s, and all the DSW’s in the area.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>When we were about to give up, we went to a Marshall’s.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>After quickly perusing the aisles, we found a pair of cream-colored, ankle strap, high heels, size ten.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I tried them on, and somehow, they fit.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I had my white shoes.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>After the wedding, when the reception was about to begin, I was hustled into a backroom to change saris.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I strapped on my white shoes and looked at myself in the mirror.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I was so made-up I could barely recognize myself.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Women were fussing over me, picking at my hair, putting more make-up on me.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Like doll,” one woman said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“You look like doll.”<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Yes, I thought.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>A doll, not a person, not me, but a doll to be dressed up and paraded around.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I went and joined my husband on the stage to greet the five-hundred wedding guests neither of us knew.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>In the corner, a gaggle of aunties was conferring in a small huddle.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>They reeled in one of the English speaking cousins and sent her up to me.<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“They want you to take of f the shoes,” she said.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>“Go take them off.”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Could she see the anger in my face beneath all that make-up?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“They make you as tall as your husband—they don’t like it.”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>“These are the one thing I get to have, the one thing that’s mine I get to have.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So what if I’m as tall as him?<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’m not taking them off.”<o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height:200%"><span style="font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-line-height:200%font-size:12.0pt;"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>She took the news back to the aunties, we shook their heads and clicked their tongues in unison.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-7210619132411500328?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/white-shoes.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-09T09:17:00.895-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79S6lVqdaI/AAAAAAAAACQ/Y-RqKaz5W5I/s72-c/DSC_9974.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"9";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:24;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:4:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:70:"tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-7407232695424203415.post-6987574907137213818";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 08 Apr 2010 21:35:00 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"food";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:6:"domain";s:31:"http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"Some Thoughts on Food-Part Two:  “Madam Doesn’t Want That”";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3734:"<a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79DERvyADI/AAAAAAAAACA/wX2WeLcxV9Q/s1600/DSC_9962.JPG"><img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 266px;" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79DERvyADI/AAAAAAAAACA/wX2WeLcxV9Q/s400/DSC_9962.JPG" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5458155014158680114" /></a><br /><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1"> </span>I’ve always liked spicy food. Even as a child, I kept a bottle of Mexican hot sauce in the fridge for my personal use.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Therefore, the following exchanges annoy the hell out of me:</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">A)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">ME:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I’ll get the chili noodles with paneer</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">INDIAN WAITER:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Madam doesn’t want that, it is spicy. [in India you are madam, no matter your age.  This takes a while to get used to]</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">ME:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>Madam does want that.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That is why she ordered it.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">B)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">DESI AUNTIE:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I made it not spicy because we have a non-Indian here (looking at me as though my non-desiness is a communicable disease)</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">MY HUSBAND:<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>That’s too bad, because she eats spicier food than I do.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal">Like the GoriWife pointed out in her most recent post, no matter how often you make desi food, you will hear the following comment and question far too often: “Wow, YOU made this?” (as though only people with Indian ancestry could ever conceivably follow a recipe).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>Honestly, I’ve been cooking Indian food since about seventh grade when my family ate an Indian buffet on a trip to Iowa City, Iowa.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I checked out Ismail Merchant’s “<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Ismail-Merchants-Passionate-Meals-Adventurous/dp/0452282322">Passionate Meals</a>” from the local library and started making all kinds of stuff.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I learned to separate ghee from the milk solids in butter, to make my own paneer, make my own yogurt, and roast cardamom pods in the oven on a cookie sheet.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I don’t do that stuff very often any more (I’m usually on a diet), but I do know how to do it.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>So do many of my American friends.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>We own cook books.</p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-tab-count:1">                </span>No matter how many times I go to India, cook Indian food, shop at the Indian store, or go to Hindi class, every time I sit down at a table in an Indian household or sit down at an Indian restaurant, Indian husband in tow, I will have to deal with people’s strange assumptions about what I eat, what I cook, and what I know.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span>I will deal with the strange moment of condescension as they tell me what I will and won’t like, and then I’ll eat what I like.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">  </span></p>  <p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> </o:p></p><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/7407232695424203415-6987574907137213818?l=bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com' alt='' /></div>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:86:"http://bigbadblondebahu.blogspot.com/2010/04/some-thoughts-on-food-part-two-madam.html";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:6:"author";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"blonde.bahu@gmail.com (Big, Bad, Blonde Bahu)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:29:"2010-04-15T11:39:19.207-07:00";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:29:"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/";a:1:{s:9:"thumbnail";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"url";s:92:"http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_CqvhCR9-IRg/S79DERvyADI/AAAAAAAAACA/wX2WeLcxV9Q/s72-c/DSC_9962.JPG";s:6:"height";s:2:"72";s:5:"width";s:2:"72";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0";a:1:{s:5:"total";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"12";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}s:39:"http://a9.com/-/spec/opensearchrss/1.0/";a:3:{s:12:"totalResults";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"28";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:10:"startIndex";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:12:"itemsPerPage";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2:"25";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:"type";i:128;s:7:"headers";a:10:{s:12:"content-type";s:34:"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8";s:7:"expires";s:29:"Mon, 29 Nov 2010 00:07:08 GMT";s:4:"date";s:29:"Mon, 29 Nov 2010 00:07:08 GMT";s:13:"cache-control";s:52:"public, max-age=0, must-revalidate, proxy-revalidate";s:13:"last-modified";s:29:"Wed, 24 Nov 2010 15:32:33 GMT";s:4:"etag";s:26:"W/CEABQn09eSl7ImA9Wx9TFkw.";s:22:"x-content-type-options";s:7:"nosniff";s:16:"x-xss-protection";s:13:"1; mode=block";s:6:"server";s:3:"GSE";s:17:"transfer-encoding";s:7:"chunked";}s:5:"build";s:14:"20090627192103";}